#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring Gentoo with Xen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "This guide describes how to start using Xen on your Gentoo system\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:27 en/xen-guide.xml:57 en/xen-guide.xml:383
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:32
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <uri link=\"http://www.xen.org/\">Xen</uri> technology allows you to run\n"
"multiple operating systems on a single physical system, govern resource\n"
"consumption and even migrate domains (which are the virtual environments in\n"
"which a guest operating system runs) from one Xen-powered system to another. Xen\n"
"requires the host operating system to support Xen (which, in this case, will be\n"
"a Linux kernel) but guest operating systems can run unmodified <e>if</e> your\n"
"hardware supports Intel Virtualization Technology (VT-x) or AMD Virtualization\n"
"Technology (SVM). Otherwise your guest operating systems must also support Xen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:43
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This guide will talk you through the configuration steps necessary to get Xen up\n"
"and running on Gentoo Linux. We will not discuss Xen itself (the Xen project has\n"
"<uri link=\"http://xen.org/support/documentation.html\">decent documentation</uri>\n"
"available) nor will we talk about specialized setups that might be very\n"
"interesting for Xen setups but are not Xen-related (like exporting Portage\n"
"through NFS, booting Linux using PXE, etc.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "Preparing Domain0"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:61
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<e>Domain0</e> is the primary domain under Xen, hosting the host operating\n"
"system which governs all other domains. In this chapter we will prepare an\n"
"existing Gentoo installation to become the host operating system in this domain\n"
"and build the Xen-powered kernel so that Gentoo is ready to host other Xen\n"
"domains.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rebuilding the Gentoo Installation?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:75
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A dramatic change that might be necessary is to rebuild the entire Gentoo\n"
"installation with a different <c>CFLAGS</c> setting. Guest operating systems\n"
"running under Xen might otherwise see major performance degradation. If you,\n"
"however, are planning on checking out Xen rather than installing it for\n"
"production use and are not terribly fond of rebuilding all programs, you can\n"
"skip this step. In this case you will notice performance degradation but you\n"
"will still be able to use Xen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><impo>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:85
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It is advised that, if you change your <c>CFLAGS</c> and build your system with\n"
"a gcc lower than version 4, you do not have <c>-Os</c> set as it has been\n"
"reported to produce broken code.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:90
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing the CFLAGS and rebuild the Gentoo installation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:91
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"~# <i>nano -w /etc/make.conf</i>\n"
"<comment>(Add -mno-tls-direct-seg-refs ONLY if you have a 32-bit dom0)</comment>\n"
"<comment>(You don't need this flag if you have a 64-bit dom0)</comment>\n"
"CFLAGS=\"-O2 -march=pentium4 -pipe <i>-mno-tls-direct-seg-refs</i>\"\n"
"\n"
"~# <i>emerge -e world</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you boot your system using an initial ramdisk (initrd) you need to\n"
"rebuild the initrd as well (which is best done by running all steps you would do\n"
"when you rebuild your kernel).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:108 en/xen-guide.xml:116
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing Xen"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:112
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Xen actually contains many components, so you'll need to install a few\n"
"packages.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:117
#, no-wrap
msgid "~# <i>emerge xen xen-tools xen-sources</i>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:123 en/xen-guide.xml:205 en/xen-guide.xml:258
#, no-wrap
msgid "Building the Kernel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next we'll build the Linux kernel with Xen support. This kernel, whose sources\n"
"are available at <path>/usr/src/linux-2.6.x.z-xen</path>, will be our main\n"
"running kernel (i.e. the one running domain 0). In the <c>XEN</c> section you'll\n"
"find drivers for all kinds of input/output, each driver having a <e>backend</e>\n"
"and <e>frontend</e> implementation available. For the domain 0 kernel you need\n"
"to select the <e>backend</e> implementation: these are used by the other\n"
"domains (who use the <e>frontend</e> drivers) to communicate directly with\n"
"the hardware.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:138
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Of course, don't forget to select <c>Xen-compatible</c> at <c>Processor type and\n"
"features</c>. If you're wondering about networking: each interface in a domain\n"
"has a point-to-point link to an interface on domain 0 (called\n"
"<path>vifX.Y</path> where X is the domain number and Y the Yth interface of that\n"
"domain), so you can configure your network the way you want (bridging, NAT,\n"
"etc.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:146
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling Xen Support for i386 Kernels"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:147
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Processor type and features  ---&gt;\n"
"      Subarchitecture Type (Xen-compatible)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/xen-guide.xml:151
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling Xen Support for x86_64 Kernels"
msgstr ""

